**SUMMARY:**  
This project explores latent space manipulation using the StyleGAN2-ADA architecture to control semantic facial attributes. By training a ResNet18 classifier on the CelebA dataset, a "Smiling" attribute detector was developed to label 5,000 synthetic images generated by the model.

The research compares two primary latent representations: the initial Z-space (Gaussian noise) and the intermediate W-space (disentangled mapping). To manipulate these spaces, "direction vectors" were calculated using both Mean Difference and Logistic Regression methodologies. Experiments conducted with the formula vnew \= vold \+ alpha \* n demonstrated that W-space is significantly more disentangled. While Z-space manipulations often led to "entanglement‚Äù where changing a smile inadvertently altered hair color or background elements, W-space allowed for precise attribute editing while preserving the subject's identity.

Furthermore, Logistic Regression proved to be the superior method for finding directions, as it identifies the optimal separating hyperplane rather than just the center of mass. Scaling the attribute intensity via alpha values revealed the limits of the model's manifold, where extreme values eventually caused image degradation.

Now we want to learn which directions in the w and z-spaces the ‚ÄúSmiling‚Äù feature lies. This direction will show us which way in the latent space the smiling feature is prevalent. We can find this direction vector with 2 methods, the first one is the mean difference between points of opposite labels:

| \#separating positive and negative indicespos\_indices \= (Y \== 1)neg\_indices \= (Y \== 0)\#calculating the direction vector (n) for z-space, using mean differencemu\_z\_pos \= Z\[pos\_indices\].mean(axis \= 0)mu\_z\_neg \= Z\[neg\_indices\].mean(axis \= 0)n\_Z\_Mean \= mu\_z\_pos \- mu\_z\_neg |
| :---- |

We do the same thing for W-space as well and have the direction vectors in both spaces. Now for the other method, we will be training a simple Logistic Regression (or SVM) model to have a boundary line between the positive and negative labeled points. The normal to that line will give us the direction of the ‚ÄúSmiling‚Äù feature:

| from sklearn.linear\_model import LogisticRegression\#setting c\_value small to prevent overfittingC\_VALUE \= 0.01 \#fitting logreg to Z-space and have a discriminating boundary line.\#the vector perpendicular to this line will be giving the smiling attribute's direction.logreg\_Z \= LogisticRegression(solver='liblinear', random\_state=0, C=C\_VALUE)logreg\_Z.fit(Z, Y)\#the coefficient array (coef\_) holds the normal vector to the boundaryn\_Z\_LogReg \= logreg\_Z.coef\_\[0\] |
| :---- |

And we do the same for W-space also. We now have 4 direction vectors. 2 for z-space, 2 for w-space. Each space has one calculated by mean difference, and one calculated by training a binary classifier and getting the normal line‚Äôs direction. Let‚Äôs normalize them before doing anything with them, because their magnitudes might affect calculations:

| def normalize\_vector(n):    return n / np.linalg.norm(n)n\_Z\_LogReg \= normalize\_vector(n\_Z\_LogReg)n\_W\_LogReg \= normalize\_vector(n\_W\_LogReg)n\_Z\_Mean \= normalize\_vector(n\_Z\_Mean)n\_W\_Mean \= normalize\_vector(n\_W\_Mean) |

Questions:

**1\. Latent Spaces: Explain the theoretical difference between Z-space and W-space. Why is W-space considered ‚Äúdisentangled‚Äù? Does your experiment support this theory?** 

**Answer:** The Z-space is the latent space of the input for GANs. It is usually distributed normally, which might cause a move in 1 dimension affecting so many features. W-space is the ‚Äúmapping‚Äù of Z-space. It is the output of some fully connected layers that took a Z-vector as the input. It is designed to be disentangled, which means that dimensions usually affect a low amount of features. Which was why the background changed so much when we used a Z-space vector but did not change so much when we used a W-space vector. So yes, the experiment supports this theory.

**2\. Method Comparison: Did SVM or Mean Difference yield better results? Why do you think that is?** 

**Answer:** SVM (Logistic Regression) yielded better results. I think that is because while Logistic Regression finds the hyperplane that separates the opposite labeled vectors, the mean difference just calculates the average position of these vectors and subtract. It only considers the center of mass. In high dimensional spaces, the average position of a group of vectors might land in sparse areas, which might cause the network to diversify from the feature we try to isolate. So the Logistic Regression method is more accurate and yields better results.

**3\. Entanglement: Show examples of ‚Äúentanglement‚Äù in your Z-space manipulations. (e.g., ‚ÄúWhen I made the face smile in Z-space, the background also became brighter‚Äù).**
